Scene setup completed:

• Created physics scene “Robot_Environment” with floor, gravity = [0  –9.81  0], and three objects: obstacle1 (2 0 1), obstacle2 (–1 0 3), target (5 0 5).  
• Added a Franka robot at (0 0 0) and a Carter robot at (0 6 0).

Below is a concise tutorial that ties everything together.

────────────────────────────────────────
1. MATLAB: Vision-based detection & obstacle avoidance
────────────────────────────────────────
A. Install the required toolboxes
   ▸ Computer Vision Toolbox  
   ▸ Robotics System Toolbox  
   ▸ Deep Learning Toolbox

B. Build the perception pipeline
```matlab
% Read image from on-board RGB camera
frame = snapshot(cam);                     % cam is a videoinput object

% Run YOLOv4 tiny (pre-trained on COCO) to detect obstacles
detector = yolov4ObjectDetector("csp-darknet53-coco");
[bboxes, scores, labels] = detect(detector, frame, 'Threshold', 0.4);

% Filter only obstacles of interest
obstIdx  = labels == "person" | labels == "chair" | labels == "bottle";
bboxes   = bboxes(obstIdx,:);
scores   = scores(obstIdx);

% Project bounding boxes to robot frame
depthMap = getDepth(camDepth);             % stereo or RGB-D camera
pc       = pcfromdepth(depthMap, camIntrinsics);
[~,centers3D] = bbox2points3D(bboxes, pc); % helper to grab 3-D centroids
```

C. Occupancy-grid & path planning
```matlab
map      = robotics.OccupancyGrid(10,10,5);      % 5 cells per meter
insertRay(map, robotPose, centers3D, 1.0);       % mark obstacles
inflate(map, 0.3);                               % safety margin

% Compute a path to the target with A* or RRT*
start  = [robotPose(1:2) 0];
goal   = [5 5 0];
planner = plannerAStarGrid(map);
path    = plan(planner, start, goal);
```

D. Local reactive avoidance (Dynamic Window Approach)
```matlab
vMax = 0.6; wMax = 1.0;
[dv, dw] = dynamicWindow(path, laserScan, vMax, wMax);
sendVelocity(robot, dv, dw);
```

Loop A→D at camera rate.

────────────────────────────────────────
2. Java physics simulation (autonomous logic)
────────────────────────────────────────
Choice of stack:  
• jMonkeyEngine (scenegraph, OpenGL)  
• dyn4j or Bullet (rigid-body physics)  
• Behavior layer written in plain Java or a BDI library such as Jadex

A. Scene bootstrap (jMonkey example)
```java
public class RobotEnvironment extends SimpleApplication {

    BulletAppState physics;  
    Node franka, carter;

    @Override
    public void simpleInitApp() {
        physics = new BulletAppState();
        stateManager.attach(physics);

        /* Floor */
        PhysicsRigidBody floor = new PhysicsRigidBody(new BoxCollisionShape(
                                   new Vector3f(50,0.1f,50)), 0);
        physics.getPhysicsSpace().add(floor);

        /* Obstacles */
        physics.getPhysicsSpace().add(makeBox("obst1", new Vector3f(2,0,1)));
        physics.getPhysicsSpace().add(makeBox("obst2", new Vector3f(-1,0,3)));

        /* Target */
        Spatial target = makeSphere("target", new Vector3f(5,0,5));

        /* Robots */
        franka = loadURDF("franka.urdf", new Vector3f(0,0,0));
        carter = loadURDF("carter.urdf", new Vector3f(0,6,0));   // second robot

        physics.getPhysicsSpace().addAll(franka);
        physics.getPhysicsSpace().addAll(carter);
    }
}
```

B. Autonomous decision-making
   1. Map each robot’s laser or depth sensor into a 2-D grid (use `jme3-lidar` or custom).  
   2. Run the same MATLAB-style planners above, ported to Java (e.g., JGraphT for A*).  
   3. Create a steering controller that publishes linear / angular velocity to the physics body.  
   4. Use shared messages (e.g., ZeroMQ) for robot-to-robot awareness.

Example velocity controller:
```java
void applyControl(PhysicsRigidBody body, float v, float w){
    Vector3f fwd = body.getPhysicsLocation().subtract(targetVec).normalize();
    body.setLinearVelocity(fwd.mult(v));
    body.setAngularVelocity(new Vector3f(0,w,0));
}
```

C. Influence of the second robot
   • Emit each robot’s predicted path as a polyline.  
   • When path overlap is detected, raise a virtual dynamic obstacle around the second robot.  
   • Re-plan or trigger reactive braking.

────────────────────────────────────────
3. Bridging MATLAB ↔ Java
────────────────────────────────────────
Option 1: TCP sockets  
   Java sends lidar & pose JSON; MATLAB replies with (v, w) commands.

Option 2: MATLAB Engine API for Java  
   Call MATLAB functions directly from Java to reuse the code in section 1.

────────────────────────────────────────
4. Next steps for experimentation
────────────────────────────────────────
1. Validate MATLAB vision offline with recorded frames from the simulator.  
2. Tune dynamic-window parameters (acceleration limits, obstacle inflation).  
3. Measure latency when the Carter robot crosses the Franka’s intended path.  
4. Collect log files in CSV, plot minimum separation distance over time.

By combining the above MATLAB perception/planning code with the Java physics scene you now have, you can iteratively refine advanced obstacle avoidance and study multi-robot interactions in realistic environments.

